Type 2 diabetes is an increasing worldwide health issue. The Pima Indian community shows significantly elevated levels of diabetes. The research “Factors That Affect Diabetes: Pima Indians” explores which demographic and clinical elements most accurately forecast the development of diabetes. Through logistic regression, the authors examine eight predictors such as pregnancies, blood pressure, BMI, glucose levels, and family history to estimate the likelihood of a diabetes diagnosis.

Importance of the Problem: Early identification of individuals at risk for diabetes enables prompt intervention, through lifestyle coaching or clinical management which can slow disease progression, reduce complications, and cut healthcare costs. For communities with limited medical access, like the Pima, simple predictive tools can guide screening priorities and resource allocation.
